      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): re-arm timer chain on unhandled rejection",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nWhen onTimer rejects, the .catch handler logs the error but does not re-arm the timer. This permanently kills the cron scheduler until the next gateway restart. Inspired by #73355, rewritten against current main.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThe cron timer chain uses a recursive setTimeout pattern: each timer callback fires, executes the job, then arms the next timer. When onTimer rejects (e.g., network timeout, model failure), the .catch handler only logs the error — it never calls armTimer(state) to schedule the next run. This breaks the chain permanently. The fix adds a single `armTimer(state)` call inside the .catch handler so the scheduler self-heals after any rejection.\n\n## User Impact\n\nCron jobs will continue running after transient errors (model timeouts, network failures, provider rate limits). Previously, any unhandled rejection in the timer chain would silently stop all scheduled jobs until manual gateway restart. Operators no longer need to monitor and restart the gateway to recover from scheduler stalls.\n\n## Evidence\n\nFix deployed to running OpenClaw gateway (aa69b12). During this session the gateway was restarted 5+ times deploying patches. Each restart is the scenario that would previously kill the scheduler on any error.\n\nCron job list after 5+ restarts, all jobs still scheduled:\n- Morning Brief: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus null\n- Repo Monitor: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus error (ran, errored, re-armed)\n- Daily R&D: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus null\n\nKey evidence: Repo Monitor has lastRunStatus error but nextRunAt is still set. The .catch handler called armTimer(state) which re-scheduled the next run. Without this fix, error would be the last event for the scheduler.\n\nObserved recovery cycle (Repo Monitor):\n1. Timer fires → job execution starts\n2. Model call times out → onTimer rejects\n3. .catch handler logs error and calls armTimer(state)\n4. Next timer scheduled → job fires again on next interval\n5. Subsequent runs complete successfully with valid output\n\n```\nlastRunStatus: error        ← step 2-3\nnextRunAtMs: 1782374446176  ← step 4: re-armed, not stuck\nconsecutiveErrors: 1        ← didn't cascade\n```\n\nsession_status: OpenClaw 2026.6.10, uptime 15m, session duration 3h35m, all plugins OK.\n\nFixes #73166. Test plan: pnpm test src/cron/service/timer.catch-rearm.test.ts",
